> I’ve had thoughts about a global rent-CPU-time grid for ages

Honest question: what would such a grid be useful for? Like Elastic Cloud, but not under one owner?

I think the idea in the linked article is way too complicated. BTC succeeded because it had a simple premise: this is a scarce fungible token that you can send to anyone. All I’ve seen about ETH smart contracts is just trying to replicate that idea without the need for massive infrastructure. Having smart contracts *and* plugins and

> Technically framing how a ledger should be constructed given arbitrary types of consensus protocols whose security relies from heuristics derived from a directed-acyclic-graph of transactions.

sounds like overkill. The last is crypto buzzword bingo, basically. 